    <td align="left" valign="top" style="padding:3px;">
         <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq1-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>What is Obstructive Sleep Apnea Syndrome?</div>
        <div id="faq1" class="icongroup1">

        <img src="images/image_1.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="left" />Apnea literally means "cessation of breath".Obstructive Sleep Apnea is simply what the words state - obstructions that happen during sleep that cause a cessation of breath.  The human upper airway is encircled by muscles.  The largest of these muscles is the tongue.  When we are awake we have tonicity or tightness in these muscles of the upper airway but during sleep these muscles relax. <br />
        <br />
        As we breathe during sleep, these relaxed muscles may vibrate causing snoring and can eventually collapse into the airway causing a decrease of airflow into the lungs.  Usually, due to this suffocation, our brain eventually wakes up out of the deeper stages of sleep and tightens up the muscles of the upper airway to again allow the airflow to return to normal. This can unknowingly happen hundreds of times a night resulting in excessive daytime sleepiness, mental impairment, cardiovascular problems and a multitude of other undesirable side effects.        </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq2-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>How can Dental Sleep Solutions dentists help?</div>
        <div id="faq2" class="icongroup1">
        As stated previously, snoring and Obstructive Sleep Apnea Syndrome are both caused by a collapse of the upper airway when the muscles relax during sleep.<img src="images/image_4.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="left" />  The largest muscle and most likely culprit for this problem is the tongue.The tongue muscle is much larger than most people may realize.  The tongue not only is present in the oral cavity; it also extends down the throat throughout most of the length of the collapsible upper airway. <br />
        <br />
        Dental Sleep Solutions dentists have obtained specialty training in custom making FDA approved adjustable dental sleep devices (DSD) that help control the collapsing of the tongue into the airway. A dental sleep device that resembles a sports mouth guard is comfortably worn in the mouth during sleep.  <br />
        <br />
        This device helps prevent the collapse of the tongue into the airway, thus decreasing snoring and Obstructive Sleep Apnea.Most people find these devices much more comfortable than CPAP (the other primary treatment for OSA and snoring) and far less invasive and more predictable than surgery.        </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq3-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>3 types of dental sleep devices</div>
        <div id="faq3" class="icongroup1">
		
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td colspan="2" valign="top" style="padding-top:5px;"> <p  style="color:#00457C"><strong>There are many FDA approved dental sleep devices.These devices can generally be divided into  the 3 categories listed below:</strong></p></td>
    </tr>
  <tr>
    <td valign="top"><!--<br /> -->
              <ul type="disc">
                <li><strong>Mandibular Advancement Devices (MAD)</strong></li>
                <ul type="circle">
                  <li style="text-align:justify"> Mandibular advancement devices are by far the most common type of dental sleep device available for snoring and OSA. They open the airway by moving the mandible (the lower jaw) forward.The tongue is attached to the lower jaw behind the chin. As the jaw is forwardly positioned, the collapsible airway is held more open by the forward movement of the tongue and other airway muscles.These devices also improve the airway by increasing the muscle activity of the tongue and other muscles of the airway.</li>
                </ul>
            </ul></td>
    <td valign="middle"><img src="images/image_5.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="right" /></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td valign="top">&nbsp;</td>
    <td valign="middle">&nbsp;</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td valign="top"><ul type="disc">
                <li><strong>Tongue Retaining Devices (TRD)</strong></li>
                <ul type="circle">
                  <li>Like MADs, tongue retaining devices also work by holding the tongue in a forward position.These devices have a similar mechanism of action but instead of moving the jaw forward like a MAD, they directly control the tongue itself.In some cases they have decreased complications as compared to MADs, but can be less comfortable.</li>
                </ul>
              </ul></td>
    <td valign="middle"><img src="images/image_2.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="right" /></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td valign="top">&nbsp;</td>
    <td valign="middle">&nbsp;</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td valign="top"><ul type="disc">
                <li><strong>Combination CPAP/Dental Sleep Device Therapy</strong></li>
                <ul type="circle">
                  <li>Often the problems associated with CPAP therapy are  due to high pressures and uncomfortable fit of the nose or face mask. Your Dental Sleep Solutions dentist can work  directly with your sleep physician to make a combination dental sleep device  that is worn with your CPAP.This custom-made  DSD will directly attach to your CPAP which makes it more comfortable and ,if combined  with jaw advancement, can be at a much lower pressure setting.</li>
                </ul>
              </ul></td>
    <td valign="middle"><img src="images/anim1.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="right" /></td>
  </tr>
</table>

		
		</div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq4-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>Why choose Dental Sleep Solutions dentists?</div>
        <div id="faq4" class="icongroup1">
        <p><img src="images/image_6.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="left" />Treating snoring and Obstructive Sleep Apnea with dental sleep devices requires specialty training.  It isn't just a matter making a mouth piece and sending you on your way.  Successful treatment begins with choosing a dentist that has the proper specialty training in Dental Sleep Medicine.  Success also relies on having the proper systems and experience to effectively utilize dental sleep therapy.</p>  

        <p>All of our Dental Sleep Solutions dentists have been personally trained by the founders of Dental Sleep Solutions, Dr. Gy Yatros and Dr. Richard Drake.  Dr. Yatros and Dr. Drake are leaders in the field of dental sleep medicine and have between them over ______years of experience in treating sleep disorders with dental sleep devices.  They are both Diplomates of the American Academy of Dental Sleep Medicine, which is a distinction for an elite group with just over 100 dentists nationally.  Your Dental Sleep Solutions dentist has been given the top-of-the-line training in dental sleep medicine.  They follow the founders' rigid protocols for making adjustable custom-made dental sleep devices that have been tried and tested to insure successful treatment of your OSA or snoring.</p>

        <p>Dental Sleep Solutions also has a network of employees to work as liaisons for your medical team.  Our staff works closely with your local physician to insure a team approach in your treatment.  Dental Sleep Solutions has gained the respect of physicians nationally for delivering quality team-oriented treatment.</p>

<p>Dental Sleep Solutions also has an ongoing commitment to insure the latest advances are tested and delivered to our patients.  Our team is solely devoted to continued improvement and delivery of the most current and optimal solutions for treating OSA with dental sleep devices.  Through our network of resources, you can rest assured that your Dental Sleep Solutions dentist continues to receive unsurpassed training on the state-of-the-art treatments available for your snoring and OSA.</p> 

<p>Our Dental Sleep Solutions dentists are committed to help identify and treat those afflicted with this serious disorder.  Through our group efforts we will exceed what anyone could accomplish individually.</p>
      </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq5-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>The Dental Sleep Solutions Experience (overview of Dental Sleep Therapy)</div>
        <div id="faq5" class="icongroup1">
        <p>To make an appointment with one of our Dental Sleep Solutions  dentists call 877 95-SNORE (877 957 -6673) or email:  info@dentalsleepsolutions.com</p>
              <p>Our dedicated staff is available 5 days a week 8:00 to 5:00  EST</p>
              <p>Once contacted, we can help answer any questions that you  may have about treating your snoring and OSA with dental sleep therapy. You may be asked to provide us with some  information to better help your Dental Sleep Solutions dentist understand your  snoring or sleep disorder breathing problems. If you have already completed a sleep study,  please have the contact information available so our team can obtain a copy of  the report from your physician prior to your arrival. You will likely be asked to complete and  bring several questionnaires with you to your appointment.These questionnaires can easily be download  from our website at _____.Once the  information is gathered we will make an appointment for a free consultation at  the most conveniently located Dental Sleep Solutions dentist in your area.</p>
              <p>Successful treatment of snoring and OSA with dental sleep  therapy relies on seeking treatment from a properly trained dentist, careful  patient screening and following successful treatment protocols.You have already successfully accomplished  the first of these goals by selecting a Dental Sleep Solutions dentist who  adheres to these standards</p>
