        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq6-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>Can my physician or regular dentist make my dental device?</div>
        <div id="faq6" class="icongroup1">
        <p><img src="images/image_7.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="left" />The American Academy of Sleep Medicine (AASM) recommends dental sleep devices as a first line of treatment option for anyone who has mild to moderate apnea and for anyone (even severe apnics) who cannot tolerate CPAP.  The AASM states that these devices should be made by a dentist who has had specialty training in the field of sleep medicine.  This prohibits physicians from making the dental devices and they should not be made by dentists without the proper training.  Our Dental Sleep Solutions dentists will work closely with your physician to make sure that your dental sleep therapy is medically successful.</p>
      </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq7-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>Is this a new medical problem and why do humans have this problem?</div>
        <div id="faq7" class="icongroup1">
        <p>Humans are the only primates known to have this condition.  Sleep disorder breathing and Obstructive Sleep Apnea have been around for many years.  But, diagnosis and treatment has been limited until recently.  It is speculated that as our faces have become more flat and as we developed changes to improve our speech we as humans have become prone to this serious disorder.  OSA can affect anyone, but certain craniofacial profiles (shape of jaw and head) can make some more susceptible.  Also an increase in weight will cause more unstable tissue in the upper airway which can lead to higher incidence of problems.  The incidence of OSA increases with age and loss of muscle tone, but it can affect a person of any age or weight.</p>
        </div>
