        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq9-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>Free Sleep Screening or Consultation</div>
        <div id="faq9" class="icongroup1">
        <p><img src="images/image_8.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="left" />Dental Sleep Solutions offers free sleep screenings and  consultations for anyone interested in learning more about snoring or OSA.If you have previously had a sleep study then  a consultation will be made to determine if you are a candidate for dental  sleep therapy </p>
                      <p>If you are a snorer, wake up gasping for air, have excessive  daytime sleepiness or other signs or symptoms of Obstructive Sleep Apnea but have not seen a professional for an evaluation then your Dental Sleep Solutions  dentist can help. Even if you think you  are just a snorer, dental sleep therapy is not recommended for anyone without  first having an evaluation for possible OSA.Contact Dental Sleep Solutions and they can schedule an appointment with  one of our dentists to perform a free sleep screening described below. </p>
                      <p>Prior to your visit you will be asked to complete several  questionnaires including a sleep and medical history (you can obtain these  online by clicking the link____).During  your free consultation a Dental Sleep Solutions dentist will review your  medical and sleep history, possibly perform a limited airway evaluation, and  help assess your risk for OSA.If your  Dental Sleep Solutions dentist feels that you qualify for further testing an  appointment will be made for you take home a portable home sleep recorder.This device is a state of the art piece of  equipment that you will wear at home for one night while sleeping. The home sleep recorder is a level 3 device  that is approved by the American   Academy of Sleep Medicine  for the diagnosis of OSA and sleep disorder breathing.The recorder gives valuable information about  breathing, snoring, blood oxygen saturation and sleep apnea events.You will be instructed to return the home  recorder the next day.</p>
                      <p>After your Dental Sleep Solutions dentist has reviewed the  home study, an appointment will be made to discuss the results.During this appointment your DSS dentist will  discuss their findings and help to determine if you are at risk for OSA.Your DSS dentists is not licensed to make a  diagnosis but he can help you determine if you should seek further medical  advice from a qualified medical sleep specialist.If further medical consultation is necessary,  then Dental Sleep Solutions can help make the proper referral to a local sleep  physician or, upon request, we may forward the results of your sleep study to a  board certified sleep physician for diagnosis (see section on diagnosis for  more information on sleep studies-link).</p>
                      <p>Once a diagnosis is made from the sleep physician then your  DSS dentist and sleep physician can help you decide the best method of  treatment for your particular situation.</p>
      </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq10-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>Diagnosis of OSA (PSG vs Home testing).</div>
        <div id="faq10" class="icongroup1">
        <p><img src="images/animate_img5.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="left" />For proper diagnosis of Obstructive Sleep Apnea or other forms of sleep disorder breathing, an overnight sleep test is necessary.  The test consists of placing leads to measure certain body functions such as breathing, blood oxygen saturation, respiratory effort, etc.  The tests vary in number of leads (which are called channels) and the method for obtaining the information.</p>

<p>Traditionally these tests have been accomplished by an attended study in a sleep facility rather than in the patient's home.  These attended studies are called  Polysomnographs (PSG) and have been used for many years for the diagnosis of sleep disorder breathing, OSA and other sleeping disorders.  Recently home testing has become approved by the American Academy of Sleep Medicine for diagnosis of OSA.  There is much debate in the medical community about which type test is the most preferable and below we will detail each type and the advantages and disadvantages of each:</p>
        <ul type="disc">
              <li><a href="polysomnograph.htm" onclick="NewWindow(this.href,'name','540','240','yes');return false" class="page">Polysomnograph (PSG)</a></li>
              <li><a href="home_sleep_study.htm" onclick="NewWindow(this.href,'name','540','340','yes');return false" class="page">Home Sleep Study</a></li>
          </ul>
      </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq11-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>Are there any side effects or complications?</div>
        <div id="faq11" class="icongroup1">
        <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="2">
          <tr>
            <td colspan="2" valign="top">    <p>As with any medical treatment there are possible complications or side effects to dental sleep therapy.  Considering the well know health risks of untreated Obstructive Sleep Apnea, most of these side effects are minor in comparison.  The 3 primary possible side effects of dental sleep therapy are tooth discomfort, TMJ or muscular discomfort, and tooth movement/bite changes.  Although other minor complications are possible, like salivation changes, these three issues encompass most of the concerns with dental sleep therapy and they will be discussed below:</p> </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td width="81%" valign="middle"> <ul type="disc">
      <li><a href="tooth_discomfort.htm" onclick="NewWindow(this.href,'name','540','240','yes');return false" class="page">Tooth Discomfort</a></li>
      <li><a href="tmj_and_muscle_discomfort.htm" onclick="NewWindow(this.href,'name','540','340','yes');return false" class="page">TMJ and muscle discomfort</a></li>
      <li><a href="tooth_movement.htm" onclick="NewWindow(this.href,'name','540','340','yes');return false" class="page">Tooth Movement/Bite Changes</a></li>
    </ul></td>
            <td width="19%"> <img src="images/animate_img6.gif" width="160" height="131" /></td>
          </tr>
        </table>
    
   
      </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq12-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>If I have TMJ problems can I still wear a Dental Sleep Device?</div>
        <div id="faq12" class="icongroup1">
        <p><img src="images/image_9.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="left" />The answer to this question is &quot;usually&quot;.Many people believe that they are not candidates for a dental sleep device if they have TMJ or jaw disorders.  Although in some instances dental sleep devices are not indicated for certain TMJ or jaw disorders, most of the time these problems do not prevent treatment with dental sleep devices.  Furthermore some of the devices can actually improve TMJ symptoms.</p>
        <p>For the cases where there are TMJ/jaw concerns, dental sleep devices are available that don't move the jaw forward and have little effect on the TMJ.Your Dental Sleep Solutions dentist will be happy to discuss your TMJ concerns and to help decide if you are a good candidate for dental sleep therapy.</p>
      </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq13-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>How much does it cost?</div>
        <div id="faq13" class="icongroup1">
        <p>Dental Sleep Solutions dentists own and operate their individual businesses separately.  They have all been trained by Dental Sleep Solutions and adhere to their proven protocols and treatment standards.  Fees for the treatments of OSA and snoring with dental sleep therapy may vary depending on the particular treatment delivered and the individual office and eographic location. All Dental Sleep Solutions offices offer a free consultation visit to see if you are a candidate for dental sleep therapy. During this visit, fees associated with your individual treatment needs with dental sleep therapy will be discussed.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq14-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>Insurance</div>
        <div id="faq14" class="icongroup1">
        <p>Many times the cost for your dental sleep therapy is covered or supplemented by medical insurance (not dental insurance). Your Dental Sleep Solutions office is trained and experienced to help you obtain your medical benefits. Through our vast network and years of experience we have become leaders in the industry at obtaining your benefits.  Our Dental Sleep Solutions team is dedicated to continually stay abreast of changes in the insurance industry and will assure that your DSS dentist has all of the training and support needed to obtain your coverage.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq15-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>Is it comfortable?</div>
        <div id="faq15" class="icongroup1">
        <p><img src="images/image_10.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="left" />Most people readily adapt to wearing the dental sleep device. After wearing the device for a short period of time it will become part of your routine and most people will hate to go to sleep without it. Compliance rates for dental sleep therapy are much higher than for other forms of non surgical treatment.  By most studies show 80 to 95% of individuals will comfortably wear their devices nightly. Once the symptom relieve is noted from the dental sleep therapy it is rare for someone to discontinue use. One of the cofounders of Dental Sleep Solutions, Dr. Gy Yatros, wears an appliance nightly. He is quoted by saying &quot;I can't sleep properly without it and it is the first thing I pack when going on a trip&quot;.</p>
      </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq16-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>Can I keep seeing my existing dentist?</div>
        <div id="faq16" class="icongroup1">
        <p><img src="images/image_11.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="left" />Yes, it is encouraged for you to continue to see your existing dentist for routine and preventative dental care.  The goal of your Dental Sleep Solutions dentist is to treat your snoring or OSA.  Although it is necessary for your DSS dentist to evaluate your teeth, their goals and your normal dentist's goals are likely very different. Your DSS dentist is evaluating your teeth to insure that they are stable enough for dental sleep therapy and they are not performing routine preventative care.  Our Dental Sleep Solutions staff will insure that we work closely with your existing dentist and will forward them copies of any pertinent records or x-rays that were completed during your visit.</p>
      </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq17-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>Do I need a custom device and why can't I just order one off TV?</div>
        <div id="faq17" class="icongroup1">
        <p>There is much evidence that custom made adjustable dental sleep devices are far more effective and comfortable than self fitting, &quot;boil and bite&quot; devices. The self fitting devices are typically much more bulky which decreases their effectiveness as well as comfort.  Furthermore most of these self fitting devices are not adjustable.  Successful dental sleep therapy is extremely dependent on the adjustability of the dental sleep device.  Without this adjustability success rates drop dramatically.</p>
        <p>OSA is a serious and life threatening medical disorder.  It is unadvisable to treat it or any other serious medical problem without proper medical supervision and guidance.  Failure to adhere to this standard could have serious medical risks.  To learn more about the process of dental sleep therapy see &quot;The Dental Sleep Solutions Experience&quot;.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq18-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>How long will the Dental Sleep Devices last?</div>
        <div id="faq18" class="icongroup1">
        <p><img src="images/image_12.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="left" lowsrc="5" />Longevity of dental sleep devices are very case dependent.  It varies depending on the specific device made, forces placed on the device and your care of the device.  Each individual Dental Sleep Solutions office have their own policies but typically any problems with the device during the first year is covered by your initial fee.  If after the first year a dental sleep device needs repair or to be reconstructed, the fee is normally less than the initial fee (which included the exam and adjustment of the device) (<a href="#" class="page">See Dental Sleep Solutions Experience for details</a>).</p>
<p>Most medical insurances will pay for construction of a new dental sleep device every two years and their longevity can be from one to many years in length.</p>
      </div>
        <div class="eg-bar"><span id="faq19-title" class="iconspan"><img src="images/minus.gif" /></span>Can you make an appliance just for snoring alone?</div>
        <div id="faq19" class="icongroup1">
        <p><img src="images/image_13.gif" width="160" height="131" hspace="5" vspace="5" border="1" align="left" lowsrc="5" />Yes, dental sleep devices work quite well at diminishing snoring. However, if you are a snorer and have never had a sleep test it is advisable to be screened or tested for the more serious disorder of OSA.- Rich fill in percent of snorers have OSA and often without them knowing it. See our section on &quot;Free Sleep Screening&quot; for more information.</p>

        <p>If a diagnosis of made of Primary Snoring (no OSA) then a dental sleep device can be made to control the snoring.  Typically the procedures needed to accomplish this goal are far less than that of someone with OSA.  Since there is no need for home sleep testing and physician consultations the resulting fee is usually lower.</p>
      </div>            
        
